Argv parsing and top-level dispatch for the `ctx-context` binary; the only file that maps CLI args to `serve`/`hook` calls and writes results, and the only place stdout is touched (always via an injected `W: Write`, never `println!`, so `clippy::print_stdout` stays un-excepted crate-wide).

`CONTRACT` is a load-bearing string constant: it is the single source of truth for the tool-contract block embedded in `CLAUDE.md`/`README.md`, and a "contracts" battery check fails if those docs drift from it — edit both together.

Path mode branches on whether `session::ENV_SESSION_ID` is set in `env`: outside a session it calls `serve::chain_for` unconditionally; inside a session it calls `serve::fresh_chain_for`, which returns `None` when the session's dedup ledger has already shown everything for that path, rendered as the literal `NOTHING_NEW` message rather than empty output. This is how a manual invocation and the PostToolUse hook share one dedup record via `crate::session`.

`dispatch<E: Env, W: Write>(env: &E, base: &Path, cli: Cli, stdin: &str, out: &mut W) -> Result<(), CtxError>` is the sole entry point. Hook mode (`cli.hook`) reads `stdin`, calls `hook::run`, and is fail-open by construction — an empty JSON result short-circuits to `Ok(())` with nothing written, and errors only surface from a broken writer. Path mode returns `CtxError::Usage` if `cli.path` is `None` and `--hook` wasn't set — the only usage-error path in the file.

`Cli::hook_mode(&self) -> bool` (via the `hook` field) tells the caller whether stdin must be drained before `dispatch` — callers must check this before consuming stdin themselves.